Author: monke_eat_banana
Content:
@im rae  From ChatGPT. I'm too lazy to look for the exact passage in the book
There‚Äôs a well-known passage in Fyodor Dostoevsky‚Äôs Notes from Underground (public domain, first published 1864) where the underground man describes how people **complain and moan about pain not simply because it hurts, but because they enjoy the attention and the reaction it provokes from others**. It comes from Part I, Chapter 4 of the novella.

Here‚Äôs an English-translated excerpt (public domain) that captures that idea:

> ‚ÄúBut what? There is pleasure even in toothache‚Ä¶‚Äù
> ‚ÄúI have had a toothache for a whole month; I know something about it. Of course, one does not suffer in silence, one moans; but these moans are not straightforward cries of pain ‚Äî they are moans with malice, and it is in that malice that the whole point lies. In those moans is expressed, firstly, all the humiliating pointlessness of your pain for our consciousness‚Ä¶ your knowledge that you are only tormenting yourself and others in vain ‚Äî and yet you continue‚Ä¶ He knows that it does him no good, and that it annoys others; yet he prolongs the moaning, because in the very act of moaning there is malicious pleasure ‚Äî a perverse joy in forcing others to feel your suffering and to pay attention to it.‚Äù
